children.content:
Programme definition: Use the HEDIPP definition (= course) = course is an approved programme of activity....
Needs to be completed within a period of time. Ranging from 3-5 years
Year 0 = a foundation year
Year 1 = normal starting standard
Year 2 = could be a placement year
Year 3 = normally a final year
Year 4 = MEng, BEng - an extra year
Programmes carry credits, e.g. 360, with av of 120 credits per year. Different intakes at diff times of year, but usually either Sept or Jan
A module can be worth 1-30 credits, some are 45, and some masters can be worth 60 credits (if inc. dissertation, say)
Year 1- usually mandatory 120 credits, all need to be passed to progress
Year 2 - 120 - mixture of compulsory or optional (usually 2/3 optional modules). Must pass all compulsory to progress. A failed optional module can be retaken in final year
Year 3 - 120 - mixture of compulsory or optional.
Mode of attendance - varies. The above is typical F/T
Sandwich course - includes sandwich
P/T course - can be 6 year course, depends on the course will be advertised accordingly.
Each course broken down into components and work items. Different weightings - exam and other types of work items -> makes up a 100% passmark.
Resits: in the event of not passing a work item, whether course or exam, student can resit.
Retake: where an *optional* module can be re-sat in its entirety. OR take an alternative module. A student can go up to 150 modules within a year.
Modules are standard no matter what programme on. They are unique and don't vary across programmes.
Other Awards: Default Awards - for certain programmes e.g. Nursing. Interim
TO DO: Capture regulations relating to programem - standard/non standard
TOB BE - need to record description of programme in new system (free text)

Credit Type - legacy
Used to be used to show placement hours attended type: standard or
Still to do: module leader, pre requisites, co requisites etc
In TO BE, we need ability to show which programmes may or may not be running in forthcoming year (ie which programmes are in suspension versus those available for registration)

Not sure if we need this concept in future to show where a programme of study 3/4 years, where years 1/2 are common with another programme, but then specific modules re a specialism then shown in brackets . We could suggest a solution,
